]|| b. 1949|| Musician, singer and songwriter||Lived at White Hart <br/>and at 40 Ferry Road, Barnes||<ref name = \"Queen\"/>||[[File:Queen And Adam Lambert - The O2 - Tuesday 12th December 2017 QueenO2121217-47 (39066610085) Cropped.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Pete Tong]]|||b. 1960||Disc jockey|||Lives in Barnes||<ref name=\"Jet\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/may/22/popandrock | title=Jet Set | work=[[The Observer]] | date=22 May 2005 | accessdate=14 September 2014 | author=Llewellyn Smith, Caspar}}</ref>||[[File:Pete tong head crop.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n||[[Stanley Tucci]] ||b. 1960|| Actor, writer, producer<br/> and film director||Lives in Barnes||<ref name=\"Tucci\">{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/stanley-tuccis-my-london-10178904.html | title=Stanley Tucci's My London | work=[[Evening Standard]] |location= London| date=16 April 2015 | accessdate=7 November 2018 | author=Fishwick, Samuel}}</ref>||[[File:Stanley Tucci 2017 Berlinale.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Julia Watson]]|| b. 1953|| Actor||Lives in Barnes||<ref name=\"Bentley\" /><ref name=\"Wroe\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/feb/21/david-harsent-life-writing-poetry | title=David Harsent: A life in writing | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=21 February 2011 | accessdate=18 December 2015 | author=Wroe, Nicholas}}</ref>||\n|}\n\n===Historical figures===\n''Those marked \u00a7 are commemorated in Barnes by a [[blue plaque]]''.<ref name=\"Blue Plaques\">{{cite web|url= http://www.visitrichmond.co.uk/blue-plaques.asp |title=Blue Plaques in Richmond upon Thames |publisher=Visitrichmond.co.uk |date= |accessdate=23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Name !! Dates!!Description!! Notes!!Refs!! Images\n|-\n|Vice-Admiral [[Alfred Carpenter]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|VC}}||| 1881\u20131955|| [[Royal Navy]] officer<br/>and a recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]]||Born in Barnes||<ref name=\"Commander Alfred Francis Blakeney Carpenter\">{{cite web| url=https://livesofthefirstworldwar.org/lifestory/6889414 |title=Alfred Francis Blakeney Carpenter \u2013 WW1 memorial and Life Story |publisher=Imperial War Museum & D C Thompson |accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>||[[File:Arthur Stockdale Cope - Alfred Francis Blakeney Carpenter.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Louis-Alexandre de Launay, comte d'Antraigues]]<br/>and his wife, [[Antoinette Saint-Huberty|Madame Saint-Huberty]] || 1753\u20131812<br/><br/><br/><br/> 1756\u20131812 ||De Launay was a French<br/> pamphleteer, diplomat spy and<br/> political adventurer during the French<br/> Revolution and Napoleonic Wars.<br/><br/> Saint-Huberty was a celebrated<br/> French operatic [[soprano]]. ||They were murdered at their<br/> country home at 27 [[The Terrace, Barnes|The Terrace]],<br/> which they had purchased<br/> about three years earlier,<br/> by an Italian servant<br/> whom they had dismissed.||<ref name=\"Bondeson2015\">{{cite book|author=Bondeson, Jan|title=Murder Houses of Greater London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WUUfCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT93|date=28 June 2015|publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-1-78462-974-8|pages=93\u201396}}</ref><ref name=\"Panorama\">{{cite web | url=http://www.panoramaofthethames.com/1829/guide/no-27-the-terrace | title=No 27, The Terrace | publisher=Panorama of the Thames | work=Mortlake and Barnes | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\" D'Antraigues\">{{cite web | url=http://www.notableabodes.com/person-abode-details/12022/louis-alexandre-de-launaycompte-dantraigues-spy_dantraigues-27-the-terrace-barnes-london | title=Louis-Alexandre De Launay, compte D'Antraigues, 27 The Terrace, Barnes, London | publisher=Notable Abodes | accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref>||[[File:Antraiguescte.gif|120px]][[File:Vigee-Lebrun Saint-Huberty.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Ninette de Valois]]||1898\u20132001|| Founder of the [[Royal Ballet]]||Lived at 14 The Terrace<br/> from 1962 to 1982.||<ref>{{cite news | title=Plaque dedicated to dancing hero Dame Ninette  | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/789145.plaque_dedicated_to_dancing_hero_dame_ninette/ | work=[[Richmond and Twickenham Times]] | author=  McDonnell, Colleen|date=9 June 2006 | accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref>\u00a7||[[File:Aankomst choreografe Dame Ninette de Vaois op Schiphol, kop, Bestanddeelnr 927-2695.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] [[Martin Dunbar-Nasmith]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|VC}} ||1883\u20131965|| Royal Navy officer<br/> and a recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]]||Born at 136 [[Castelnau, London|Castelnau]]||<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/12891478.World_War_I_submariner_and_captain_of_HMS_Iron_Duke_honoured_with_blue_plaque/ | title=World War I submariner and captain of HMS Iron Duke honoured with blue plaque in Barnes | work=[[Richmond and Twickenham Times]] | date=16 April 2015 | accessdate=28 October 2015 | author=Proto, Laura}}</ref>\u00a7||[[File:Captain M E Nasmith, Vc, Rn - 1918 Art.IWMART1335.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n| Major [[John Freeman (British politician)|John Freeman]] ||1915\u20132014|| Politician, diplomat and broadcaster||Lived in Barnes||<ref name=\"Purcell\">{{cite news | url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/politics/2013/03/john-freeman-face-face-enigma | title=John Freeman: Face to face with an enigma | work=[[New Statesman]] | date=7 March 2013 | accessdate=21 December 2014 | author=Purcell, Hugh}}</ref>|| [[File:John Freeman MP.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[James Henry Greathead]]|| 1844\u20131896|| Railway engineer and pioneer of tunnelling||Lived at 3 St Mary's Grove,<br/> Barnes, from 1885<br/> to 1889||\u00a7||[[File:JAMES HENRY GREATHEAD 1844-1896 Railway and Tunnelling Engineer lived here 1885-1889.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|Lieutenant-General [[Robert Ballard Long]]|| 1771\u20131825||Officer of the [[British Army|British]]<br/>and [[Hanoverian Army|Hanoverian Armies]] ||Retired to his house<br/> on The Terrace||<ref name=\"ODNB\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/16974?back= Chichester, H. M. \"Long, Robert Ballard (1771\u20131825)\", rev. Stearn, Roger T, first published 2004; online edn, May 2008.] ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]''. Retrieved 27 November 2007.</ref>||[[File:Robert Ballard Long (1771-1825).jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Ralph Moor|Sir Ralph Moor]]|| 1860\u20131909|| [[High Commissioner]]<br/> of the British [[Southern Nigeria Protectorate]]||Poisoned himself at<br/> The Homestead<br/> on Church Road in 1909||<ref name=\"ODNB Moor\">{{cite ODNB |last=Hargreaves |first=John D. |authorlink=John D. Hargreaves  |title=Moor, Sir Ralph Denham Rayment (1860\u20131909) |year=2004 |id=35086}}</ref>||[[File:Ralph Denham Rayment Moor.jpg|120px|[[Ralph Moor|Sir Ralph Moor]]]]\n|-\n| [[Colin Patterson (biologist)|Colin Patterson]]|| 1933\u20131998|| [[Palaentologist]]||Lived in Barnes||<ref>{{cite journal | author = Fortey, R A | authorlink = Richard Fortey|title = Colin Patterson. 13 October 1933&nbsp;\u2013 9 March 1998 | year = 1999 | journal = Biographical Memoirs of Fellows of the Royal Society | volume = 45 | pages = 367\u2013377 | jstor = 770282 | doi=10.1098/rsbm.1999.0025| doi-access = free }}</ref>||\n|-\n| [[Lyon Playfair]]|| 1818\u20131898||Professor of chemistry and Liberal MP||Lived at 26 Castelnau Villas<br/>(98 Castelnau), Barnes in 1851,<br/> while  taking part in organising<br/> the [[Great Exhibition]]||<ref name=\"People M-S\">{{cite web | url=http://www.barnes-history.org.uk/celMS.pdf | title=People of Mortlake, Barnes and East Sheen: M&nbsp;\u2013 S | publisher=Barnes and Mortlake History Society | accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>|||[[File:Lyon Playfair.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Albert Frederick Pollard]] ||1869\u20131948|| Historian and founder of the [[Historical Association]]||Lived at 7 St Mary's Grove||<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>||\n|-\n|[[Sir John Power, 1st Baronet]]|| 1870\u20131950||Businessman and<br/> Conservative MP for [[Wimbledon (UK Parliament constituency)|Wimbledon]]||Lived at 1 Queen's Ride, Barnes,<br/> from 1908 to 1919||<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>||\n|-\n|Sir [[John Russell Reynolds]], 1st Baronet ||1828\u20131896|| British [[neurologist]] and [[physician]],<br/> President of the<br/> [[Royal College of Physicians]], 1893\u201395|| Occupied Rose Cottage, Barnes Green,<br/> as a weekend cottage<br/> from about 1862 to 1870||<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>||[[File:John Russell Reynolds.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|  [[Robert Willis (physician)|Robert Willis]] ||1799\u20131878|| Scottish physician, librarian, and medical historian||Lived and practised at [[The Homestead, Barnes|The Homestead]]<br/> on Church Road from 1846<br/> until his death in 1878||<ref name=\"People\">{{cite web | url=http://www.barnes-history.org.uk/celTY.pdf | title=People of Mortlake, Barnes and East Sheen:  T\u2013Z | publisher=Barnes and Mortlake History Society | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>||\n|}\n====Actors====\n[[File:Peter Mayhew 2015.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Peter Mayhew]]]]\n*[[Joss Ackland|Rosemary Ackland]] (1951\u20132002), actress, lived in Barnes.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n[[File:Phyllis Calvert.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Phyllis Calvert]], actress]]\n*[[Phyllis Calvert]] (1915\u20132002), actress, lived in Barnes.<ref name=\"114 lenin imports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.leninimports.com/phyllis_calvert.html |title=Phyllis Calvert Biography (1915\u20132002) |publisher=leninimports.com |date= |accessdate=3 September 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Jimmy Edwards]] (1920\u20131988), comedy actor and writer, was born in Barnes.<ref name=\"Edwards\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/1375514/index.html |title=Edwards, Jimmy (1920\u20131988) |last=Oliver |first=John |website=BFI Screenonline}}</ref>\n*[[Rik Mayall]] (1958\u20132014), actor, writer and comedian, lived and died in Barnes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jun/09/rik-mayall-dies-funniest-man-generation-young-ones|title=Rik Mayall the funniest man|author=Ellis-Petersen, Hannah|accessdate=9 June 2013|work= [[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Sudden\">{{cite news | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/11266325.Comedy_idol_Rik_Mayall_dies_suddenly_at_his_home_in_Barnes/?ref=rss | title=Comedy idol Rik Mayall dies suddenly at his home in Barnes | work=[[Richmond and Twickenham Times]] | date=9 June 2014 | accessdate=9 June 2014 | author=Dyduch, Amy}}</ref>\n*[[Peter Mayhew]] (1944\u20132019), who played [[Chewbacca]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' films, was born and brought up in Barnes.<ref name=\"Mayhew\">{{cite news |url=\nhttp://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2005-10-17-mayhew-citizenship_x.htm | title='Star Wars' actor becomes U.S. citizen | work=[[USA Today]] | date= 17 October 2005|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n*[[John Moody (actor)|John Moody]] (c. 1727\u20131812), actor, lived at 11 [[The Terrace, Barnes]], from about 1780 until his death. He is buried at [[St Mary's Church, Barnes]] with his two wives.<ref name=\"Brown 122\">{{cite book | title=Barnes and Mortlake Past, with East Sheen | publisher=Historical Publications | author=Brown, Maisie | year=1997 | pages=122 | isbn=978-0-948667-46-6}}</ref>\n* [[Jimmy Perry]] (1923\u20132016), actor and scriptwriter, co-creator of the TV series ''[[Dad's Army]]'' and ''[[Hi-de-Hi]]'', was born in Barnes.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11062341 | title=Obituary: Jimmy Perry | work=[[BBC News]] | date=23 October 2016 | accessdate=29 October 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Jon Pertwee]] (1919\u20131996), ''[[Doctor Who]]'' actor, had a family house in Barnes.<ref name=\"Anstead\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/8289088/Sean-Pertwee-Why-I-never-expected-to-be-Doctor-Who.html | title=Sean Pertwee: 'Why I never expected to be Doctor Who' | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=30 January 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2014 | author=Anstead, Mark | location=London}}</ref>\n[[File:Terry-Thomas in Where Were You When the Lights Went Out.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Terry-Thomas]]]]\n*[[Terry-Thomas]] (1911\u20131990), actor, lived in Barnes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/sep/20/biography2|title=Review: Bounder! and 50 Years of Carry On|first=Michael|last=Coveney|date=19 September 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Frank Thornton]] (1921\u20132013), actor ([[Captain Peacock]] in the BBC comedy ''[[Are You Being Served?]]''), lived and died in Barnes.<ref name=\"Thornton\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-21828965 | title=Are You Being Served? actor Frank Thornton dies aged 92 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=18 March 2013 | accessdate=23 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Artists, architects and designers====\n*[[Thomas Allom]] (1804\u20131872), architect, artist, topographical illustrator and a founding member of what became the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (RIBA), designed [[Holy Trinity Barnes]] and lived locally at 1 Barnes Villas (now 80 Lonsdale Road), Barnes, where he died on 21 October 1872.<ref name=\"Architect\">{{cite web | url=http://www.barnes-history.org.uk/architects.pdf | title=Local architects | publisher=Barnes and Mortlake History Society | accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref><ref>Brooks, Diana. \"Allom, Thomas (1804\u201372)\", ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' (Oxford, UK: OUP, 2004) [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/410 Retrieved 13 March 2016. Pay-walled.]</ref>\n*[[Gillian Ayres]] {{postnominals|country=GBR|CBE| RA}} (1930\u20132018), artist,  grew up in Barnes.<ref name=\"Hilton\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2018/apr/11/gillian-ayres-obituary |title=Gillian Ayres obituary  |last=Hilton |first=Tim |date=11 April 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=19 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.artnet.com/people/artnet-asks-abstract-painter-gillian-ayres-72708|title=artnet Asks: Abstract Painter Gillian Ayres|publisher=[[Artnet]]|author= Rubio, Lorraine|date= 25 August 2014|accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Sidney Richard Percy]] (1821\u20131886), landscape painter, lived with his father at 32 Castelnau Villas (92 Castelnau), Barnes, from 1845 to 1856.<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>\n*[[Henry William Pickersgill]] (1782\u20131875), portrait painter, lived at Nassau House, Barnes Green, from about 1854 to 1857. He is buried in [[Barnes Cemetery]] with his wife, who died in 1857.<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>\n*[[Kurt Schwitters]] (1887\u20131948), artist, lived at 39 Westmorland Road, Barnes.<ref name=\"Schwitters\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/blue-plaques/kurt-schwitters/ |title=Schwitters, Kurt (1887\u20131948 |website=[[English Heritage]] |access-date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\u00a7\n====Musicians====\n*[[Marc Bolan]] (1947\u20131977), singer, songwriter, musician and poet, lived at Lonsdale Road, Barnes.<ref name=\"L-A Jones\">{{Cite book |last=Jones |first=Lesley-Ann |title=Ride a White Swan: The Lives and Death of Marc Bolan |publisher=[[Hodder & Stoughton]] |year=2012 |isbn=978 1 444 75880 1 |location=London}}</ref> \n*[[George Frederick Handel]] (1685\u20131759) lived at the house of Mr Mathew Andrews in Barn Elms in the summer of 1713.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Handel,_George_Frederick_(DNB00)|title=Handel George Frederick|author=Maitland, John Alexander Fuller; Squire, William Barclay|date=|publisher=|volume=Volume 24|accessdate=15 May 2019|via=Wikisource}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D-ycAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT678&ots=e6uQ1ZEY4n&dq=Barn+Elms+Matthew+Andrews&hl=nl&pg=PT678#v=onepage&q=Barn+Elms+Matthew+Andrews&f=false|title=George Frideric Handel: Volume 1, 1609\u20131725: Collected Documents|first1=Donald|last1=Burrows|first2=Helen|last2=Coffey|first3=John|last3=Greenacombe|first4=Anthony|last4=Hicks|date=20 February 2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|accessdate=15 May 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\u00a7\n[[File:Holst House.jpg|thumb|right|175px|The house in Barnes where [[Gustav Holst]] lived between 1908 and 1913. The house has a [[blue plaque]] in his honour<ref name=\"Blue Plaques\"/>]]\n*[[Gustav Holst]] (1874\u20131934), composer, lived at 31 Gretna Road, Richmond from 1903 to 1908, then moved with his family to 10 The Terrace, Barnes until 1913.<ref name=\"Royal Minstrels\">{{cite book | title=Royal Minstrels to Rock and Roll: 500 years of music-making in Richmond | publisher=[[Museum of Richmond]] | author=Boyes, Valerie | year=2012 | location=London}}</ref>\u00a7\n*[[Freddie Mercury]] (1946\u20131991), musician, vocalist and lyricist of the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]], shared a house at 40 Ferry Road.<ref name=\" Kokozej\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mercury-and-queen.com/officialbiography.htm | title=Official Biography | publisher=Daria Kokozej | work=The Freddie Mercury Story | accessdate=2 May 2014 |author1=Gunn, Jacky |author2=Jenkins, Jim }}</ref><ref name=\" Wreckage\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.queenpedia.com/index.php?title=Wreckage |title=Wreckage: History |last= Davis, Andy: Stuart, John S |website=Queenpedia.com |access-date=27 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Sportspeople====\n*[[Ebenezer Cobb Morley]] (1831\u20131924), sportsman, regarded as the father of The Football Association and modern football,<ref name=\"Rudd\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/article3694775.ece|title=The father of football deserves much more|author=Rudd, Alyson|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> lived in [[The Terrace, Barnes|The Terrace]] at Barnes and is buried in Barnes Cemetery.<ref name=\"Search\">{{cite news | title=Search for founding fathers of football proves fruitless | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/archive/2013/05/14/10416647.Search_for_founding_fathers_of_football_proves_fruitless/ | work=[[Richmond and Twickenham Times]] | date=14 May 2013 | accessdate=4 July 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610210736/http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/archive/2013/05/14/10416647.Search_for_founding_fathers_of_football_proves_fruitless/ | archive-date=10 June 2015 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n====Writers====\n*[[Henry Fielding]] (1707\u20131754), novelist, lived at Milbourne House, Barnes Green in about 1750, when writing ''[[Amelia (novel)|Amelia]]''.<ref name=\"People E-G\">{{cite web | url=http://www.barnes-history.org.uk/celEG.pdf | title=People of Mortlake, Barnes and East Sheen: E\u2013G | publisher=Barnes and Mortlake History Society | accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref>\u00a7\n*[[Judith Kerr]] (1923\u20132019), author and illustrator, and her husband, [[Nigel Kneale]] (1922\u20132006), scriptwriter, both lived in Barnes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/8463548/The-cats-whiskers-interview-with-Judith-Kerr.html|title=The cat's whiskers: interview with Judith Kerr|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=16 January 2016|location= London|author= [[Cassandra Jardine|Jardine, Cassandra]]|date=26 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/data/im147-ms11631|title=Literary papers of playwright and author Thomas Nigel Kneale including screenplays, scripts, correspondence and press reviews \u2013 Archives Hub|access-date=2018-01-26}}</ref>\n*[[Eric Newby]] (1919\u20132006), travel author, grew up in Castelnau Mansions, Barnes.<ref name=\"A history of writing\">{{cite web | url=http://www.barnesvillage.com/literary-barnes/a-history-of-writing.html | title=A history of writing | publisher=Barnes Community Association | work=Barnes: the village on the river | year=2010 | accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Barbara Pym]] (1913\u20131980), novelist, lived at 47 Nassau Road.<ref name=\"A history of writing\"/>\n*[[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]] (1751\u20131816), playwright, poet, theatre owner and MP, who owned [[Downe House, Richmond Hill]],<ref name=\"NHLESheridan\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1249949 |desc=Downe House|accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> took a house on [[The Terrace, Barnes|Barnes Terrace]] in 1810 when his son Tom was living at [[Milbourne House]].<ref name=\"People M-S\"/>\n*[[Dodie Smith]] (1896\u20131990), author of ''[[I Capture the Castle]]'' and ''[[The Hundred and One Dalmatians]]'', lived in Riverview Gardens.<ref name=\"A history of writing\"/>\n*[[Colin Welland]] (1934\u20132015), Oscar-winning screenwriter of ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'', lived in Barnes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/the-betrayal-of-a-heritage-1615893.html|title=\"Colin Welland came from his home in Barnes, southwest London\", para.6|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=31 December 2013|location=London|author= [[Simon Kelner|Kelner, Simon]]|date=16 April 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Demography and housing==\nTo give an equal councillor number and electorate, the [[wards of the United Kingdom|wards]] in the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] are multi-councillor but aim to be equally sized. To achieve this, approximately half of one of the two wards covering modern Barnes also falls within the boundaries of neighbouring [[Mortlake]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43023 |title=Map of the parish boundaries. Introduction to history of the hundred|author=[[Henry Elliot Malden|Malden, H E]] (editor) |publisher=[[Institute of Historical Research]] |year=1912 |work=Part of the [[Victoria County History]] Surrey: Volume 4 |accessdate=21 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''2011 Census homes'''\n|-\n!Ward !!Detached  !!Semi-detached!!Terraced!!Flats and apartments!!Caravans/temporary/mobile homes/houseboats!!Shared between households<ref name=ons/>\n|-\n|Barnes||\t277\t||\t1,198\t||\t996\t||\t1,784\t||\t0\t||\t41\n|-\n|Mortlake and Barnes Common||\t167\t||\t547\t||\t1,765\t||\t2,453\t||\t1\t||\t8\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''2011 Census households'''\n!Ward !!Population !!Households !!% Owned outright !!% Owned with a loan!!hectares<ref name=ons/>\n|-\n|Barnes||10,299\t||\t4,151\t||\t32\t||\t26\t||\t265\t\n|-\n|Mortlake and Barnes Common||10,919\t||\t4,771\t||\t27\t||\t32\t||\t185\t\n|-\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"\">\nFile:London Wetland Centre Building, Barnes, UK - Diliff.jpg|Entrance to the visitors centre at the [[WWT London Wetland Centre]]; on the left is the statue of [[Peter Scott]] by Nicola Godden\nFile:Bolan Bust.jpg|[[Bolan's Rock Shrine|Marc Bolan's shrine]], on what would have been his 60th birthday, 30 September 2007\nFile:Bulls Head Barnes.jpg|Pub and jazz venue [[The Bull's Head, Barnes|The Bull's Head]]\nFile:BarnesPond693-4.JPG|Barnes Pond with the [[Sun Inn (Barnes)|Sun Inn]] in the background\nFile:Barnes Methodist Church - geograph.org.uk - 1309196.jpg|[[Barnes Methodist Church]]\nFile:Barney - Barn Elmes Plane MG 4859 sm.jpg|The [[Barn Elms]] [[London Plane]] tree known as \"Barney\", thought to be the oldest example of the species in London and officially designated a \"[[Great Trees of London|Great Tree of London]]\"\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Barnes Hospital, London|Barnes Hospital]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Barnes, London}}\n* [http://www.barnes-history.org.uk/ Barnes and Mortlake History Society]\n* [http://www.barnes-ca.org/ Barnes Community Association]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100819045926/http://www.barnesvillage.com/index.php Barnes Village website]\n* {{OpenDomesday|TQ2176|barnes|Barnes}}\n\n{{LB Richmond}}\n{{London Districts}}\n\n[[Category:Barnes, London| ]]\n[[Category:Areas of London]]\n[[Category:Conservation areas in London]]\n[[Category:Districts of London on the River Thames]]\n[[Category:Districts of the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Wards of the London Borough of Ric