ine.org/ World Seagrass Association]\n*[http://www.seagrassli.org/ SeagrassLI]\n*[http://www.unepscs.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=52&Itemid=84 Seagrass Science and Management in the South China Sea and Gulf of Thailand]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20181215171446/http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/toc/mae/27/4 ''Marine Ecology'' (December 2006)] - special issue on seagrasses\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110727065713/http://www.marineconservationcambodia.org/Marine-Species-Photographic-Database/Cambodian-Marine-Life/Cambodian-Marine-Plants/Seagrasses.html/ Cambodian Seagrasses]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110130032609/http://seagrassproductivity.com/ Seagrass Productivity - COST Action ES0906 ]\n*[http://www.fish.wa.gov.au/Documents/recreational_fishing/fact_sheets/fact_sheet_seagrasses.pdf Fisheries Western Australia - Seagrass Fact Sheet]\n\n{{aquatic ecosystem topics|expanded=marine}}\n\n[[Category:Seagrass| ]]\n[[Category:Plant common names]]\n[[Category:Roofing materials]]\n\n[[de:Seegras]]\n", "name_user": "Bennwm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeagrass", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seagrass"}
{"title_page": "Goluzino, Syamzhensky District, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Goluzino\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Syamzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|53|N|41|33|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/syamzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u044f\u043c\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Goluzino''' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Korobitsynskoye Rural Settlement, [[Syamzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 75 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Syamzha]] is 55&nbsp;km, to Georgiyevskaya is 13&nbsp;km. Pirogovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Syamzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Syamzhensky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Goluzino\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Syamzhensky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|53|N|41|33|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/syamzhenskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u044f\u043c\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Goluzino''' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0437\u0438\u043d\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Korobitsynskoye Rural Settlement, [[Syamzhensky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 75 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Syamzha]] is 55&nbsp;km, to Georgiyevskaya is 13&nbsp;km. Pirogovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Syamzhensky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Syamzhensky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goluzino,_Syamzhensky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Tuqaq", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name= Tuqaq Temur Yalig\n|title      = [[Bey]]\n|royal house= [[Oghuz Yabgu State|Oghuz Yabgu]]\n|father     = Kerequchi\n|death_date={{circa}} [[924 AD]]}}\n{{anchor|Flag}}\n[[File:Kinik.png|alt=|thumb|[[Tamgha]] of the [[Oghuz Turks|Oghuz]]-[[Turkmen people|Turkoman]] tribe of [[K\u0131n\u0131k (tribe)|Kinik]], to which Tuqaq belonged]]\n{{History of the Turks pre-14th century}}\n'''Tuqaq''' or Tuqaq beg ({{script|Arab|\u062f\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0642 \u062f\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u06cc\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0642}} or Duqaq ([[Turkish language|Turkish]] : Dukak bey; [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]] : Dukak beg or Dukak Demir yayl\u0131; [[full name]]: ''Duqaq Temur Yalig'') was a ''subashi'' (commander-in-chief) in [[Oghuz Yabgu State]]<ref>Refik Turan, Sel\u00e7uklu Tarihi El Kitab\u0131 (Seljuk History Handbook), published by Grafiker Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 2018, p-27</ref> and the father of [[Seljuk (warlord)|Seljuq]], eponymous founder of the [[Seljuk dynasty]]. His great-grandson [[Tughril Beg|Tughril beg]] would establish [[Great Seljuk Empire]] in the 11th century.<ref>S.G.Goodrich, \"Modern History, from the Fall of Rome, A.D. 476, to the Present Time\", published by Morton and Griswold, page 112: \"In year 1042, Togrul beg, a Turkoman chief, of the tribe of Seljuk, having made himself a master of Khorasan...\"</ref> \"Tuqaq Temur Yalig\" literally means \"Iron [[Bowery|bow]]\" or \"with an iron bow\" in [[old Turkic language]].\n\n==Origin==\n\nNot much is known about Tuqaq or his early activities, information is sparse and dubious, most of which come from sources written later, especially after the [[Battle of Dandanaqan|establishment of the Seljuk Empire]] or from [[oral tradition]]. It is widely believed, however, that he and his famous descendants were from the [[K\u0131n\u0131k (tribe)|Qiniq tribe]] of the [[Oghuz Turks]]<ref>Jackson, P. (2002). \"Review: The History of the Seljuq Turkmens: The History of the Seljuq Turkmens\". Journal of Islamic Studies. Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies. 13 (1): 75\u201376.</ref>. His father's name was Kerequchi, who was a renowned local blacksmith or master of making tents (yurts). Somewhat reliable sources also tell us that at the latter stages of his life, Tuqaq was in the military service of the [[Oghuz Yabgu State]] and held important position among the Oghuz Turks. His nickname \"Iron bow\" tells us that he most probably was not an ordinary soldier. In Oghuz culture, arrow and bow are considered as a \"sign of sovereignty\" and considering Duqaq's nickname, he was a commander-in-chief of the Oghuz army{{Sfn|Turan|\u00d6zg\u00fcdenli|2018|p=27}} or probably a powerful statesman, who most definitely had great power and influence in [[Oghuz Yabgu State]].\n\n==Affiliations==\n\nPersian epic \"Maliqnamah\" (Book of Kings) mentions a warrior called Tuqaq who was in the service of the [[Khazars|Khazar]] [[Khagan]]. Probably, Tuqaq served the Khazars until a dismal decline of [[Khazar khaganate|their state]], which intensified under the pressure of [[Cumans]],<ref name=\"epic\">{{cite web |title=Epic of the past years |url=http://old-russian.chat.ru/01povest.htm |website=Old Russian literature (in Russian)}}</ref> and then made alliance with the Oghuz Yabgu state with which he stayed for the rest of his life.\n\nDespite holding high position in Oghuz Yabgu, it is known that Tuqaq had sour relations with other influential leaders of the state, as he objected the policy of raiding other Oghuz tribes (turks)<ref name=\"herth\">{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=224}}</ref>. Tuqaq's son Seljuk most probably had similar views and later this may have triggered other Turks within the Oghuz Yabgu state to join Seljuk's Kinik tribe when they split from Oghuz Yabgu and moved to a new homeland in [[Transoxiana]] and the vicinity of [[Merv]]. It would later carry significant importance as Seljuk Turkomans became a formidable force in the region, enabling them to challenge Ghaznavids and consequently, start their quick journey to greatness.    \n\n==Death== \n\nIt is believed that Tuqaq died in 924. After Tuqaq's death, Oghuz Yabgu appointed his son, Seljuk, as the commander-in-chief of the Oghuz army<ref>{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=225}}</ref>.\n\nIn 961, Seljuk, together with his Kinik tribe and some other Oghuz tribes left the Oghuz state with their cattle, sheep and horses to [[Mawarannahr|Mawerannakhr]]. It was approximately after that he and his tribe adopted [[Islam]] and later refused to pay taxes to Oghuz Yabgu (as they were not Muslims) and established their own independent beylik (small country)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=225}}</ref>. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Khazar Khaganate]]\n* [[Oghuz Yabgu State]]\n* [[Oghuz Turks]]\n* [[Qiniq]]\n* [[Seljuq dynasty]]\n* [[Seljuq Empire]]\n* [[Tughril Beg]]\n\n{{Seljuk dynasty}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Seljuk rulers]]\n[[Category:Khazar military history]]\n[[Category:1009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name= Tuqaq Temur Yalig\n|title      = [[Bey]]\n|royal house= [[Oghuz Yabgu State|Oghuz Yabgu]]\n|father     = Kerequchi\n|death_date={{circa}} [[924 AD]]}}\n{{anchor|Flag}}\n[[File:Kinik.png|alt=|thumb|[[Tamgha]] of the [[Oghuz Turks|Oghuz]]-[[Turkmen people|Turkoman]] tribe of [[K\u0131n\u0131k (tribe)|Kinik]], to which Tuqaq belonged]]\n{{History of the Turks pre-14th century}}\n'''Tuqaq''' or Tuqaq beg ({{script|Arab|\u062f\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0642 \u062f\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u06cc\u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0642}} or Duqaq ([[Turkish language|Turkish]] : Dukak bey; [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]] : Dukak beg or Dukak Demir \u00fda\u00fdly; [[full name]]: ''Duqaq Temur Yalig'') was a ''subashi'' (commander-in-chief) in [[Oghuz Yabgu State]]<ref>Refik Turan, Sel\u00e7uklu Tarihi El Kitab\u0131 (Seljuk History Handbook), published by Grafiker Yay\u0131nlar\u0131, 2018, p-27</ref> and the father of [[Seljuk (warlord)|Seljuq]], eponymous founder of the [[Seljuk dynasty]]. His great-grandson [[Tughril Beg|Tughril beg]] would establish [[Great Seljuk Empire]] in the 11th century.<ref>S.G.Goodrich, \"Modern History, from the Fall of Rome, A.D. 476, to the Present Time\", published by Morton and Griswold, page 112: \"In year 1042, Togrul beg, a Turkoman chief, of the tribe of Seljuk, having made himself a master of Khorasan...\"</ref> \"Tuqaq Temur Yalig\" literally means \"Iron [[Bowery|bow]]\" or \"with an iron bow\" in [[old Turkic language]].\n\n==Origin==\n\nNot much is known about Tuqaq or his early activities, information is sparse and dubious, most of which come from sources written later, especially after the [[Battle of Dandanaqan|establishment of the Seljuk Empire]] or from [[oral tradition]]. It is widely believed, however, that he and his famous descendants were from the [[K\u0131n\u0131k (tribe)|Qiniq tribe]] of the [[Oghuz Turks]]<ref>Jackson, P. (2002). \"Review: The History of the Seljuq Turkmens: The History of the Seljuq Turkmens\". Journal of Islamic Studies. Oxford Centre for Islamic Studies. 13 (1): 75\u201376.</ref>. His father's name was Kerequchi, who was a renowned local blacksmith or master of making tents (yurts). Somewhat reliable sources also tell us that at the latter stages of his life, Tuqaq was in the military service of the [[Oghuz Yabgu State]] and held important position among the Oghuz Turks. His nickname \"Iron bow\" tells us that he most probably was not an ordinary soldier. In Oghuz culture, arrow and bow are considered as a \"sign of sovereignty\" and considering Duqaq's nickname, he was a commander-in-chief of the Oghuz army{{Sfn|Turan|\u00d6zg\u00fcdenli|2018|p=27}} or probably a powerful statesman, who most definitely had great power and influence in [[Oghuz Yabgu State]].\n\n==Affiliations==\n\nPersian epic \"Maliqnamah\" (Book of Kings) mentions a warrior called Tuqaq who was in the service of the [[Khazars|Khazar]] [[Khagan]]. Probably, Tuqaq served the Khazars until a dismal decline of [[Khazar khaganate|their state]], which intensified under the pressure of [[Cumans]],<ref name=\"epic\">{{cite web |title=Epic of the past years |url=http://old-russian.chat.ru/01povest.htm |website=Old Russian literature (in Russian)}}</ref> and then made alliance with the Oghuz Yabgu state with which he stayed for the rest of his life.\n\nDespite holding high position in Oghuz Yabgu, it is known that Tuqaq had sour relations with other influential leaders of the state, as he objected the policy of raiding other Oghuz tribes (turks)<ref name=\"herth\">{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=224}}</ref>. Tuqaq's son Seljuk most probably had similar views and later this may have triggered other Turks within the Oghuz Yabgu state to join Seljuk's Kinik tribe when they split from Oghuz Yabgu and moved to a new homeland in [[Transoxiana]] and the vicinity of [[Merv]]. It would later carry significant importance as Seljuk Turkomans became a formidable force in the region, enabling them to challenge Ghaznavids and consequently, start their quick journey to greatness.    \n\n==Death== \n\nIt is believed that Tuqaq died in 924. After Tuqaq's death, Oghuz Yabgu appointed his son, Seljuk, as the commander-in-chief of the Oghuz army<ref>{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=225}}</ref>.\n\nIn 961, Seljuk, together with his Kinik tribe and some other Oghuz tribes left the Oghuz state with their cattle, sheep and horses to [[Mawarannahr|Mawerannakhr]]. It was approximately after that he and his tribe adopted [[Islam]] and later refused to pay taxes to Oghuz Yabgu (as they were not Muslims) and established their own independent beylik (small country)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Herth |first1=William |title=The Secret Alchemy of Mary Magdalene |date=2005-2007 |publisher=Ormus Publications and Booksellers LLC |isbn=0-9793737-0-0 |page=225}}</ref>. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Khazar Khaganate]]\n* [[Oghuz Yabgu State]]\n* [[Oghuz Turks]]\n* [[Qiniq]]\n* [[Seljuq dynasty]]\n* [[Seljuq Empire]]\n* [[Tughril Beg]]\n\n{{Seljuk dynasty}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Seljuk rulers]]\n[[Category:Khazar military history]]\n[[Category:1009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Nedim Ardo\u011fa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuqaq"}
